WORLD CUP USA '94 / ROUND OF 16; SPOTLIGHT; HE HAS PERFECT PITCH ON THE SOCCER 
PITCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM D. MONTALBANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If you're still among the American majority who hasn't yet figured out the 
difference between a free kick and a goal kick, here's a cheering word from 
tenor Placido Domingo.He was among the crowd on hand in Washington on Saturday 
to see Spain advance to the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
 "What soccer and opera have in common is that they both unite people. You can 
enjoy either without understanding a word," Domingo opined. 
</P>
<P>
 Like most Europeans, Domingo has also spent time on the field. 
</P>
<P>
 "I used to be a goalie but now I play up front," he joked. "Tenors are 
strikers, really, always pushing forward." WILLIAM D. MONTALBANO 
</P>
