<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; DISASTER RESPONSE VOLUNTEERS SOUGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thousand Oaks residents interested in learning how to fight fires, use ham 
radios and rescue hard-to-reach victims are invited to join the city's Disaster 
Assistance Response Team, known as DART. 
</P>
<P>
 The 30 team members are recruiting new members this summer and hope to begin 
general disaster-preparedness training in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
 Emergency response experts will teach monthly classes on such subjects as 
disaster psychology and damage assessment. Participants also learn to perform 
first aid and cardiopulmonary resuscitation. 
</P>
<P>
 In Thousand Oaks, DART members also volunteer to help out with special events, 
such as traffic control during the Fourth of July fireworks show and the annual 
Conejo Valley Days. 
</P>
<P>
 The group's meeting, usually at City Hall or the East Valley sheriff's 
station, are held on the third Thursday of each month and are open to the 
public. For information, call Stacy Park in the city manager's office at 
496-8652. STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
