<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHRISTOPHER MAY VISIT VIETNAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Vietnam's deputy foreign minister said Sunday that U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher might visit Vietnam, paving the way for full diplomatic 
relations with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
 U.S. officials visiting Vietnam to try to resolve the fate of American 
servicemen declared missing in action during the Vietnam War mentioned a 
possible visit by Christopher to Hanoi, Deputy Foreign Minister Le Mai said. 
</P>
<P>
 Christopher would be the most senior official to visit Vietnam since the end 
of the war in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
 President Clinton lifted a U.S. trade embargo against Vietnam in February, and 
the two sides have agreed to open diplomatic liaison offices in each others' 
capitals soon. Full diplomatic relations are expected to follow. 
</P>
<P>
 Mai, who has had two meetings with the U.S. delegation since its arrival 
Friday afternoon, said the talks have been constructive and both sides are 
pleased with the results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
